      {
        "turn_number": 1,
        "role": "interviewer",
        "content": "Hey — thanks for jumping in. I’m here to help you configure an AI agent that writes code the way *you* would. No templates, no scripts — just a conversation to get your style, values, and preferences down so the agent feels like an extension of your brain.\n\nLet’s start simple: What’s the *biggest problem* you’re trying to solve with this agent? What’s the one thing you want it to do — consistently — that you’re not currently getting done (or doing yourself) in your day-to-day work?",
        "timestamp": "2026-02-23T23:22:19.184Z"
      },
      {
        "turn_number": 2,
        "role": "user",
        "content": "Implement roadmap items end-to-end with tests, docs, and reliable CI-ready outcomes.",
        "timestamp": "2026-02-23T23:22:40.530Z"
      },
      {
        "turn_number": 3,
        "role": "interviewer",
        "content": "Thanks for sharing your goal — that’s a strong, outcome-oriented vision. To make sure the agent writes code the way *you* would, I want to understand a bit more about your engineering style. \n\nLet’s start with the big picture: What’s the *primary problem* you’re trying to solve by implementing roadmap items this way — with tests, docs, and CI-ready outcomes? Is this for a team, a personal project, or something else? And what does “success” look like for you? For example, is it about shipping quickly, or ensuring reliability and maintainability?",
        "timestamp": "2026-02-23T23:22:50.961Z"
      },
      {
        "turn_number": 4,
        "role": "user",
        "content": "[User requested to skip this topic]",
        "timestamp": "2026-02-23T23:23:21.185Z"
      },
      {
        "turn_number": 5,
        "role": "interviewer",
        "content": "Got it — you’re focused on execution and outcome. That’s a great starting point.\n\nLet’s shift gears: When you’re reviewing code or working with an AI agent, what’s the *one thing* you notice first when reading someone else’s code — whether it’s your own or someone else’s? Is it readability? Test coverage? Naming? Or something else entirely? \n\n(Just curious — this helps me understand your code quality bar.)",
